Engineering /ˌenjəˈniriNG/
The action of working artfully to bring something about.

Engineering is more than machinery and code. It’s intricate mechanisms that, when perfectly assembled, come together to create something astounding. Over ten years ago, Interesting Engineering was founded to help readers uncover these finely woven systems — to help them better understand what makes things tick.

Our mission was to use innovative storytelling to highlight the enthralling inner workings of the latest scientific breakthroughs, technological innovations, cultural phenomena, and more. 

Today, we still stand by that mission.

We don’t just bring you breaking news. We uncover the mechanisms that make these developments possible, transforming how you see the world of today to ensure you’re prepared for the world of tomorrow.

The slogan of this channel is “in search of”, meaning that it doesn’t support a fixed view or teaching, but instead explores many different (and often contradicting) topics. An elected Member of Parliament, former Minister of State for External Affairs and former Under-Secretary-General of the United Nations, Shashi Tharoor is the prize-winning author of twelve books, both fiction and non-fiction, including the classic The Great Indian Novel (1989), India: From Midnight to the Millennium (1997), Nehru: The Invention of India (2003) and The Elephant, the Tiger and the Cellphone: Reflections on India in the 21st Century (2007). A widely-published critic, commentator and columnist (including for The Hindu, The Times of India and Newsweek), Shashi Tharoor served the United Nations during a 29-year career in refugee work, peace-keeping, the Secretary-General's office and heading communications and public information.  He has won India's highest honour for Overseas Indians, the Pravasi Bharatiya Samman, and numerous literary awards, including a Commonwealth Writers' Prize. [For more on 
 Tharoor, please see www.shashitharoor.in.]

snippet.description:
Einzelgänger's main goal is to entertain, inspire, resonate and share the love of ideas with others. The slogan of this channel is “in search of”, meaning that it doesn’t support a fixed view or teaching, but instead explores many different (and often contradicting) topics. Dogma and narrow-mindedness are not what we’re about, as we try to stay open to a wide range of ideas.

You could see Einzelgänger as a portal to many different subjects in the areas of philosophy, religion, and psychology, from analyzing movies to exploring Stoic ethics and Carl Jung to looking at the world through a Taoist lens. Some topics are presented superficially, while others have more depth to them. 

*Disclaimer: The material provided by Einzelgänger is designed for educational and entertainment purposes only. This is not providing clinical/medical services via this communications medium. You should not rely on the information on this channel in lieu of consultation with your own health professional.
